### Converting to a common denominator

This is our sum:

$\dfrac{2}{\blueE{x-3}}+\dfrac{5}{\maroonE{x+1}}$

We can multiply both the numerator and the denominator of the first expression by $\maroonE{x+1}$, and multiply both the numerator and the denominator of the second expression by $\blueE{x-3}$. This way, they will have the common denominator $(\blueE{x-3})(\maroonE{x+1})$.

$\begin{align}
&\phantom{=}\dfrac{2}{\blueE{x-3}}+\dfrac{5}{\maroonE{x+1}}
\\\\
&=\dfrac{2}{\blueE{x-3}}\cdot\dfrac{\maroonE{x+1}}{\maroonE{x+1}}+\dfrac{5}{\maroonE{x+1}}\cdot\dfrac{\blueE{x-3}}{\blueE{x-3}}
\\\\
&=\dfrac{2x+2}{(\blueE{x-3})(\maroonE{x+1})}+\dfrac{5x-15}{(\blueE{x-3})(\maroonE{x+1})}
\end{align}$

### Adding the like expressions

Now that the expressions have a common denominator, we can add them!

$\begin{align}
&\phantom{=}\dfrac{2x+2}{(\blueE{x-3})(\maroonE{x+1})}+\dfrac{5x-15}{(\blueE{x-3})(\maroonE{x+1})}
\\\\
&=\dfrac{(2x+2)+(5x-15)}{(\blueE{x-3})(\maroonE{x+1})}
\\\\
&=\dfrac{7x-13}{x^2-2x-3}
\end{align}$

